// Semantic direction:
// homotopi_typeteori interprets types as homotopy spaces and terms as points.
// identitetstype Id(A,a,b) is the type of proofs that a and b are equal in A.
// refl_sti is the trivial path refl : a = a.
// sti_sammensetning p · q composes path p : a=b with q : b=c to get a=c.
// kontraktibel_type has exactly one element up to homotopy — the contractible center.
// proposisjonstype has at most one element: any two elements are equal.
// sett_type has trivial identity types (all paths between equal elements are themselves equal).
// truncasjon_nivå measures the complexity of the identity types.
// proposisjonal_truncasjon ‖A‖₋₁ squashes A to a proposition (classical existence).
// circle_type is the simplest non-trivial HIT: one base point and one loop path.
// push_out is the homotopy pushout — generalizes many constructions (suspension, join, etc.).
// univalensaksiomet: (A ≃ B) ≃ (A = B) — equivalent types are equal as types.
// type_ekvivalens is a pair of functions f:A→B and g:B→A with homotopies g∘f ~ id and f∘g ~ id.
// funext_fra_ua: funksjon_extensjonalitet follows from univalence — if f x = g x for all x, then f = g.
// homotopi_fiber of f:A→B at b:B is Σ(a:A). f(a) = b — the preimage with proof.
// eilenberg_maclane_rom K(G,n) is the space with only πₙ = G and all other homotopy groups trivial.
// blakers_massey is a connectivity theorem with important consequences for homotopy theory.

// Primitive flow:
// Univalence: gitt iso : A ≃ B (f, g, η, ε)
//   ua(iso) : A = B -- aksiomet gir stien
//   transport(ua(iso), a : A) : B = f(a) -- transport langs stien er f
// Circle rekursjon: data S¹ = base | loop : base = base
//   eliminer f : S¹ → A for A:Type:
//   f base = pt : A; f (loop i) = γ i for γ : pt = pt i A
// Fundamental gruppe: π₁(S¹, base) ≅ ℤ
//   fra HoTT-perspektiv: winding number telles av loop-sammensetninger
// Proposisjonal truncasjon: bevis ∃x:A. P(x) i hott
//   = element av ‖Σ(x:A).P(x)‖₋₁
//   tilgang: kun om P er en proposisjon selv (kan ikke ekstrahere vitnet)

// This defines HoTT: path types as identities, homotopy levels (contractible/propositions/sets),
// higher inductive types (circle/pushout), propositional truncation, the Univalence Axiom
// with function extensionality, fiber theory, Eilenberg-MacLane spaces, and Blakers-Massey.
